REASONS FOR JUDGMENT

WILSON J

INTRODUCTION

On 24 and 26 February 2026 various applications were before me. They were –
(a) the applications in paragraphs 7, 8, 9 and 10 of the wife's amended application in a proceeding dated 23 February 2026; and

(b) the applications in paragraphs 14 to 26 of the husband's response filed 19 January 2026 to the wife's application in a proceeding dated 21 October 2025.

The mainstay of debate focused on the wife's applications for orders for the sale of the property situated at S Street, Suburb T in the State of Victoria ("the former matrimonial home"). That was the gravamen of paragraph 7 of the wife's amended application in a proceeding. Paragraph 8 concerned proposed orders about the conduct of the sale of the former matrimonial home, paragraph 9 concerned the application of the proceeds of sale of the former matrimonial home and paragraph 10 concerned the production of documents sought by the wife.
It was uncontroversial that the husband is the registered proprietor of the former matrimonial home. The wife presently resides in it along with the children. The wife fears that funds are insufficient to meet mortgage instalments. She sought orders for the sale of the former matrimonial home. The husband resisted the wife's application for the sale of the former matrimonial home contending that a friend was willing to advance funds to him by way of loan to enable any short-term liquidity issues to be overcome. The wife argued that the former matrimonial home is the asset of the greatest value so it must be protected for the purposes of this s 79 application.
The husband advanced an alternative contention to the effect that he will consent to the sale of the former matrimonial home if three consecutive defaults under the mortgage are demonstrated.
For the reasons that follow, I am of the view that the husband's proposed lender has not provided any real proposal of substance and that the former matrimonial home must be sold with the proceeds of sale to be deposited into a trust account. The precise terms of the orders that emerge from these reasons must be formulated in accordance with the request made by counsel for the wife.

THE RELEVANT FACTUAL SETTING

Many factual matters relevant to this present dispute were recorded in my reasons handed down on 2 May 2025 in Unterbrink & Unterbrink,[1] so I will confine the issues pertinent to this application to the matters canvassed in the wife's affidavit made 23 January 2026, her financial statement of the same date, the husband's affidavit affirmed 19 February 2026, his financial statement made 30 January 2026 and the statutory declaration of Mr W made 23 February 2026.

SELLING THE FORMER MATRIMONIAL HOME

The wife deposed to her desire to sell the former matrimonial home from paragraph 37 of her affidavit. Relevantly paraphrased, she said the following –
(a) she had lived at the property with the children;

(b) title to the former matrimonial home is encumbered by three loan facilities, described by her as an equity loan facility and two home loans;[2]

(c) she was a borrower under the loan facility she called the equity loan;

(d) in June 2022, the husband drew down on the loan styled the equity loan, triggering interest to accrue;

(e) she said she was unable to make all interest payments due under all loans so the lender, ANZ, granted a form of moratorium which has now come to an end;[3]

(f) the sum of $428,616 is currently outstanding under the loan styled the equity loan;

(g) the sum of $629,609 is currently outstanding under the loan styled the big home loan;

(h) the sum of $72,941 is currently outstanding under the loan styled the small home loan;[4]

(i) the monthly commitment required to maintain possession of the former matrimonial home is $7,878.37;

(j) if the former matrimonial home were let by a tenant, the weekly rental in the sum of $1,200 to $1,300 could be obtained according to the real estate agent DD Real Estate;

(k) according to the statement of claim prepared by the husband dated 2 June 2025, his taxable income is $69,600 per annum equating to a monthly income of $4,708;

(l) according to the husband's 19 January 2026 affidavit, his gross monthly income from September 2024 to date is $8,481.70 with a monthly net income of $6,531.70;

(m) the wife deposed to her weekly income being $7,889 and her weekly expenses being $13,296 which amount of expenses does not include the children's private school fees (one at an annual rate of $39,438 and the other at an annual rate of $28,620);

(n) she said her private borrowings amount to $47,051 borrowed from Mr AA, $10,000 borrowed from Mr W and a further sum of $15,000 borrowed from Mr AA along with $30,000 borrowed from Ms CC; and

(o) she has sold shares generating $15,282.57 and she cashed in a life insurance policy deriving $80,000 both of which sums were applied in reducing amounts owed under various loans.

She asserted that the husband has been derelict in complying with his disclosure obligations. She gave an example of an interest she believed he had in a hospital in City U, India. She also deposed to an interest she believed he had in a business called EE Business. She also deposed to the husband being named as the sales and marketing director of an organisation called FF Pty Ltd because the wife said his name appears on the entity's website. She said he has made no discovery of the husband's involvement in the hospital, the other business or FF Pty Ltd. She said she seeks further disclosure.
The wife's financial statement revealed a collection of entries in Part B. They were as follows–
(a) her total average weekly income was $7,889;

(b) her total personal expenditure was $9,208;

(c) the total value of property owned by her was $115,631.50;

(d) the total gross value of her superannuation was $389,612;

(e) the total of her liabilities was $685,634; and

(f) she has a zero figure for her financial resources.

The husband's 19 February 2026 affidavit addressed his current financial position between paragraphs 7 and 33. In essence, he deposed to the following –
(a) until April 2019 he was employed by GG Limited receiving $107,000 per annum or thereabouts;

(b) he was employed by HH Limited as its chief executive officer, earning the equivalent of $3,700 per month gross;

(c) in September 2024 he worked as a consultant with JJ Business which provided consultancy services to FF Pty Ltd;

(d) he was not in fact a director of FF Pty Ltd; and

(e) from September 2024 to date he has been self-employed earning income of $135,707.

He said he owes no amount by way of child support.
While producing no documentary evidence to verify the assertion, the husband deposed to the wife enjoying multiple holidays in Australia and he said she travelled to Country V in July as well as to India in late 2025. He gave no evidence of the source of funds of those trips. The husband asserted that the wife has failed to produce documentation referable to her receipt of income from the HH Limited partnership. He said the wife now wishes to sell the most valuable asset of the matrimonial pool in Australia being the former matrimonial home. He said that the wife's interest in the HH Limited partnership had been valued at over AUD $2,400,000. He said he wishes to retain the former matrimonial home because it is close to his children's school.
He said he wishes sole possession of the former matrimonial home with a view to letting it. He reasoned that rental income would meet 80% of the current mortgage sums and he could meet any shortfall, currently in the vicinity of $1,000 per month. He said that based on information gained from a firm of real estate agents, he could let the former matrimonial home within two to four weeks.
So far as the means to be deployed in avoiding the sale of the former matrimonial home, the husband deposed to the involvement of his friend, Mr W. He said the following –
I wish to retain the former matrimonial home and avoid its sale. By way of a financial safeguard, I have sought the assistance of my close friend [Mr W] who is fully aware of my financial circumstances and my objective to retain the former matrimonial home. [Mr W] has agreed to loan me money from time-to-time (if and when required by me), to address any outstanding arrears on the ANZ Home Loan accounts #[...]58, #[...]39 and #[...]87, the shortfall payment or any further payment required to be made to the bank. [Mr W] has agreed to lend me such funds on the condition that I execute an appropriate Loan Agreement with him, under which I shall repay the principal and interest at 6% at the conclusion of these proceedings. [Mr W] and I are still in the process of drawing up the relevant loan agreement, which I expect to be done by the end of February 2026. In the interim, [Mr W] has provided me with a letter outlining his intentions to loan me money. As I understand it, if I am permitted to have sole possession of the former matrimonial home and if I borrow money from [Mr W] to meet any shortfall in mortgage payments on the former matrimonial home, the funds borrowed by me will not be a liability of the matrimonial pool. Now produced and shown to me, and marked with the letters “[Mr Unterbrink]MRU-5” is a copy of the said letter.
Mr W, whose statutory declaration was made on 23 February 2026, addressed the loan the husband deposed to in the husband's affidavit. Relevantly paraphrased, Mr W declared as follows –
(a) he is a friend of the husband;

(b) he has agreed to assist the husband by agreeing to provide a loan of up to AUD $50,000, on the basis that Mr W and the husband execute an appropriate loan agreement to be drafted by Mr W's legal representatives;

(c) interest will be at the rate of 6%;

(d) repayment of the loan will be at the end of the husband's family law litigation; and

(e) Mr W is in the process of engaging Satori Law to draft the loan agreement.

During debate on 24 February 2026, the status of the information imparted by Mr W assumed considerable importance, especially whether by its terms, the observations made in Masters v Cameron[5] were engaged and whether the arrangements which Mr W declared amounted to an agreement to agree and therefore were void for uncertainty. Those issues are addressed in the passages that follow.

SUBMISSIONS

Each party's case outline made various superficial contentions yet those propositions were not fully explored in the applications before me. No written submissions were provided. That said, Mr Robins KC, who appeared with Dr Mort of counsel for the applicant, along with Mr Baker of counsel who appeared for the respondent, fully and skilfully ventilated all proper submissions for which I was most grateful. In précis form, Mr Baker's submissions were as follows –
(a) the registered proprietor of the former matrimonial home is the husband the value of which as given by the husband is $1,978,392;

(b) at present, neither party has the capacity to service the repayments owing on the former matrimonial home;

(c) the husband asserts that the wife's interest in the HH Limited partnership is 25% whereas the wife contends that her interest in that partnership is 5%;

(d) the only order sought on the return of this application is the sale of the former matrimonial home and the deposit of the proceeds thereof in an interest bearing trust account;

(e) the wife's application is purely one based on asset preservation;

(f) as matters presently stand, neither party can service the loans resulting in interest and fees accumulating;

(g) on the husband's formulation, the house can only be kept if it is rented and if Mr [W] advances a loan;

(h) notices of default have been served;

(i) however, any mortgagee sale procedure has not yet been activated;

(j) absent a moratorium by the mortgagee, the longer the loans remain unpaid the greater is the prejudice to the parties by the "inevitable and inexorable diminution of the asset pool" (Mr Baker's words);

(k) the husband promises to sell if there are three defaults;

(l) a caveat has been lodged on title by the husband's solicitors which is likely to impact the settlement of any sale;

(m) whether the equitable mortgage supporting the caveat amounts to an interest in land of the sort canvassed in Avco Financial Services Limited v White[6] remains to be seen;

(n) the wife has sufficient funds if the property is sold to find alternative accommodation for herself and the children; and

(o) the [Mr W] loan proposal is wholly devoid of details.

On behalf of the husband, Mr Robins KC advanced a collection of propositions. They may be condensed into the following –
(a) the wife's financial position in the evidence is a movable feast;

(b) having conceded in her pleadings that the value of the former matrimonial home was, as the husband asserted (estimated at $1.85 million), the wife is disingenuous to suggest that the amount in issue is now somehow different;

(c) the wife has travelled extensively in recent times so her submissions that she is in dire financial straits should be rejected;

(d) the business HH Limited is a going concern so the wife's interest in it is likely to attract some value;

(e) if the husband defaults for three consecutive months in his repayment obligations to the mortgagee he will agree to sell;

(f) the husband wants to avoid a sale by reason of a latent capital gains tax obligation to which he is or may be exposed;

(g) the husband does not accept that after trial an order will be made under s 79 for the sale of the property;

(h) the evidence of the CGT liability is not fully before the court;

(i) it is clear that in this case an excess of assets over liabilities exists;

(j) to the extent that there will be evidence in this case of foreign law, foreign law is adduced as factual evidence rather than opinion evidence; and

(k) disclosure by both parties remains in issue in this case.

Mr Robins KC condensed the position in précis form. The following appears at page 28 of the transcript –
... But in circumstances where there’s a significant surplus of assets over liabilities, where the husband is offering in effect to take over 100 per cent of the mortgage 25 liability going forward from the time of possession, and in circumstances where he’s providing for a default sale upon three months of noncompliance with the mortgage instalment, the lesser risk of injustice here wholly falls on my client, if there was to be a sale order now, whereas the worst outcome to the wife – under my client’s orders, any interest liability to [Mr W] is solely to the husband’s account and will 30 not form any part of the adjustments he seeks under section 79 at trial.

And if there is a default on his part, which causes some erosion to the matrimonial property pool, that’s a matter that your Honour will be able to offset against the husband’s interest under section 79 anyway. So there is very little downside 35 whatsoever to the wife. For her, the upside in the sale order is to essentially obtain a position where there is no asset of substance in this country other than a pool of money produced by the sale. And that will then require both parties to live in rental accommodation pending the trial, whereas the husband is at least seeking to preserve the primary asset pending trial in circumstances where there is adequate evidence 40 that he has the capacity to do so with the assistance of [Mr W].

And if he doesn’t, the condign consequence would be that there will be a sale order. So it’s very hard to understand on a commercial basis why the wife has taken the position that she has taken. And that’s why we invite your Honour to draw the 45 inferences that we’ve suggested....

CONSIDERATION

Logically, if not imperatively, the first issue for determination is the wife's application for the sale of the former matrimonial home. In my view, orders must be made in accordance with paragraph 1 of the wife's application in a proceeding. I take that view for several reasons. In making the observations below, I am bound to apply the ratio of a collection of appellate authorities that caution against a judge dealing with a contested interlocutory application from making findings of fact, except with great circumspection. Among those authorities is Redmond & Redmond[7] and SS & AH.[8] Despite there being no evidence of a formal nature about the identity of the registered proprietor of the former matrimonial home, it was conceded that the husband is the registered proprietor. It was also conceded that the husband and wife were separated under one roof for a time and that the wife and children have since left the former matrimonial home in consequence of which the husband presently lives in yet the wife is required to meet the ongoing burden of mortgage repayments in respect of it.
A significant issue arose about the parties' capacity to service the loan facilities between them and ANZ. The husband asserted that it might be possible for the monthly instalments to be met if a tenant is installed to rent the former matrimonial home and if the husband undertakes yet further borrowings, this time with funds provided by Mr W. Mr W has not yet entered into a loan agreement in respect to the sum of $50,000 to which he deposed in his statutory declaration. Documentation evidencing the loan is yet to be created. It is likely that negotiations will take place during which the terms of any such loan will be hammered out. At the moment, even a heads of agreement for the loan is not yet in evidence, nor does it exist.
While Mr W and the husband appeared confident that no impediment exists to the formulation, agreement and execution of loan documentation, at present their agreement in relation to any such loan is little more than an agreement to agree and therefore void for uncertainty.[9] Nothing has yet been agreed about the duration of the agreement, interest rests, and events of default rendering payment of all outstanding sums due. Whether or not the arrangement between Mr W and the husband is even one in respect of which the parties intend to create legal relations remains to be seen as well. Even if they do, it also remains to be seen whether the terms of a loan agreement are enforceable, having regard to the fact that the parties may not be seen as being at arm's-length. Of course, it is unnecessary to descend into that at the present juncture.
The wife seeks orders for the sale of the former matrimonial home because she is unable to afford the repayments associated with its retention, so she says. The husband disputes her assertions in that regard. He says that her interest in the HH Limited partnership has historically provided cash in amounts which would enable her to meet the mortgage debts presently burdening the former matrimonial home. The husband also says that the wife has spent sums on overseas and local holidays as well as spending money on the children's private school fees. It is important to recognise that the husband did not adduce reliable evidence by way of quantification of the sums he said had been exhausted by the wife in the manner asserted. For the most part, his evidence on those matters was premised on his belief that amounts in an unquantified sum or in an unverified amount were spent. I did not regard those contentions as persuasive. I am unwilling to place any particular emphasis on assertions which are not verified by credible evidence. Conversely, in her financial statement the wife gave as the total of her liabilities $685,634 and the total value of her assets $115,631.50.
The husband's contentions in support of his application to retain the former matrimonial home were underpinned by three propositions. First, he said the former matrimonial home is the most valuable asset in Australia and must not be sold because he seeks orders at trial conferring upon him all right, title and interest in the former matrimonial home which he says will not be possible if the former matrimonial home is sold. Second, he said that in respect of any shortfall in the cashflow needed to service the ANZ facilities, borrowings can be met from rental income derived from letting the former matrimonial home thereby preserving that property from any enforcement proceeding by ANZ. Third, he said the court should be slow to conclude that the wife is unable to meet sums due to ANZ because she is entitled to profits derived from the HH Limited partnership and on the husband's case her entitlement is as to 25%, rather than 5% as the wife asserts.
As to the first contention, I reject it. While true the former matrimonial home may well be a valuable asset and the most valuable asset in Australia, the wife's proposal is not to destroy the asset but rather to convert it to cash and for the cash derived from its sale to be deposited into an interest-bearing trust account. In other words, by the sale of the former matrimonial home, the enlargement of outgoings (mostly mortgage dues) are cauterised, crystallised and can be realised. In my view, where parties are unable to afford to keep an asset such as a home, it must be either refinanced in such manner as they can afford or the asset must be sold. The husband said he wants to press for orders at trial that he receives the former matrimonial home absolutely. Naturally, that could only ever emerge as a possibility if in the meantime the mortgagee does not set in train steps to sell the property and to do so under the provisions of the Transfer of Land Act. Already one or more notices of default have been served in relation to defaults under the loan facilities. That provides a very fragile foundation to expect that between this day and the trial of the proceeding, which is unlikely to be this calendar year, further defaults will not be experienced.
As to the second proposition, precisely why the former matrimonial home should be immune from realisation now went unexplained. There seems to be truth in the contention advanced by Mr Baker of counsel that the husband fears that a capital gains tax liability will arise if the former matrimonial home is sold. The husband wants to avoid that. He may well wish that but I have to balance that desire against the wife's evidence that the parties simply cannot presently afford to keep the property. Debts beyond a capital gains tax liability can be discharged if the former matrimonial home is sold. To my way of thinking, the wife's contention on the point predominates over the wishes of the husband concerning a capital gains tax liability. I am not at all persuaded that rental income will be received, and even if it is that the amount involved will enable the husband to pay his mortgagee on a regular basis.
As to the third proposition, I am not presently in a position to determine what percentage is properly due to the wife as her partnership share in HH Limited. She says it is 5%, whereas the husband said it is 25%. That issue must be determined at trial but not now. In any event, the whole of the evidence necessary to determine that matter is not presently before me. It is impossible for me to conclude on this application that the interest of the wife in the HH Limited partnership which the wife derives enables her to meet outgoings in the manner asserted by the husband. In my view, the evidence establishes that the former matrimonial home cannot be held by the husband as the liability in respect of it exceeds the parties' ability to service the loans. It must be sold.
The orders proposed by the wife in paragraphs 7, 8 and 9 of her application in a proceeding dated 21 October 2025 as amended must be made. The orders proposed by the husband in paragraphs 14 to 24 of the husband's response filed 19 January 2026 are dismissed.
In paragraph 10 of her application in a proceeding the wife sought production of the documents set out in annexure A attached to the application in a proceeding. No annexure A was attached to the document as filed. Beyond a general grievance being agitated by both parties to the effect that disclosure by each has been defective, it is difficult to identify the precise documents in respect of which production is sought. Mr Baker asked for an opportunity to formulate the precise terms of orders if his client's arguments were successful. They have been. He should have an opportunity to formulate the orders she seeks.
So far as disclosure issues are concerned, it is fair to say that the adequacy of disclosure continues to bedevil this case. The husband sought not only documentation but also information set out in paragraph 25 of his response. The "information" sought was akin to interrogation. The Federal Circuit and Family Court of Australia (Family Law) Rules 2021 permit a form of interrogation, as I held in Jess & Jess (No 18),[10] although an order in those terms is not as of right. In that case, sustained dereliction of duty in respect of the duty of disclosure was one reason supporting the making of the interrogation orders. Paragraph 25 of the husband’s response is a request for information about such issues as –
(a) persons residing in the former matrimonial home over specific periods;

(b) whether (as a direct question) one or more named persons resided at the former matrimonial home with the wife; and

(c) documents supportive of specific allegations

and other matters, the significance of which in this s 79 application was near impossible to ascertain. No submissions or case law was advanced on behalf of the husband as providing a jurisdictional foundation for the orders sought.

In view of the fact that the wife did not advance submissions concerning annexure A disclosure, so too did the husband not advance submissions in respect of the orders sought in paragraph 25 of his response, I am willing to give the parties 14 further days within which to file submissions on those two aspects - annexure A in respect of the wife and paragraph 25 in respect of the husband.
Otherwise, I direct the parties to bring in a minute by noon on Wednesday, 4 March 2026 to give effect to these reasons.
